Technological determinism is a term that encompasses many different ideas in practice, from the fact that technology drives development or the technological imperative in the strict view that the fate of man is driven by the basic concept of the laws of nature and how they manifest in technology.
Most interpretations of technological determinism have two general ideas in common: that technology development itself follows a path that is largely beyond cultural or political influence, and that technology in turn has “effects” on societies that are original, rather than social.
For example, one could say that the motorized car necessarily lead to the construction of roads.
However, a nationwide road network is not economically sustainable for just a small amount of cars, so new production methods are being developed to reduce the cost of owning a car.
Mass ownership of cars also leads to a higher incidence of accidents on the roads, leading to the invention of new healthcare technologies to repair damaged bodies.
